2 DRW
.BR
This command allows a variety of graphic representations of the
line-following process to be displayed on the close-up screen
for diagnostic purposes. The only command
(except those already available via the command macros)
which is relevant to users is:
.P5
DRW B n
.BL
where n is the number of master points (counting backwards from the
end of the buffer)
which should be drawn. See also the 'B' macro which draws the whole
buffer (note that you CANNOT type 'B n').
.BL
2 DRN
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 MPcommand
.BR
MP (FB10)
.BL
When first given this  command  puts  a  cursor  up  on  the
screen.   Subsequent MP commands will add master points to
the digitised line.
.BL
2 BCC
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 BACk
.BR
If FB15 is pressed while line-following, HELP mode is entered
and FB15 is redefined to be macro BB (q.v.). If FB15 is pressed
again, LASERAID allows the user to 'roll' along the digitised
data using the tracker ball. FB15 is then defined to be BACk.
Subsequent presses of FB15 will cause the last master point
in the current feature to be deleted.
.BL
It should be noted that master points deleted in this way
cannot be recovered (except, of course, by re-digitising that
portion of the line).
.BL
2 ROL
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 NOR
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 CURsor
.BR
CURsor
.BR
CLOse-up
.BL
Draw a close-up view of the area around the LASERTRAK cursor on
the Tektronix screen, then put up the Tektronix cursor. When a
character is typed the LASERTRAK cursor is moved to the equivalent
position. This command can be used for fine positioning of the
LASERTRAK cursor.
.BL
2 MANual
.BR
Master points may be created using the close-up screen and
cross-hairs. Typing MANual causes a facsimile of the area
around the LASERTRAK cursor to be drawn on the close-up
screen, also showing the end of the current digitised
line if relevant. Additional data points may be created
by moving the cross-hairs to the required position and
pressing the space bar. Typing 'E' rather than a space
exits from this mode and line-following can resume
if required.
.BL
2 FC
.BR
FC n - feature code
.BL
Change the feature code of the current feature after it
has been started, over-riding the value obtained from
the function button. This command should be given with
line following paused (using FB15). The feature code
is not patched into the IFF file until the feature is
accepted.
.BL
2 ACB
.BR
ACB n - Ancillary Code Base
.BL
This is a privileged command in HELP mode which is only used
for patch file interaction. It is not available to the user.
.BL
2 AC
.BR
AC type value [text] - Ancillary Code
.BL
Include the specified AC in the current feature.
.BL
The AC 'value' is examined for a decimal point, and
is stored as a real number if one is found. If the AC 'type' is 3
(INCLUDING the ACB), this is treated as a special case and its
value is ALWAYS stored as a real number.
.BL
2 SAC
.BR
SAC type value [text] - Standing Ancillary Code
.BL
This is a privileged command in HELP mode which is only used
for patch file interaction. It is not available to the user.
.BL
2 FCF
.BR
FCF - Feature Code for Function buttons
.BL
This is a privileged command in HELP mode which is only used
for patch file interaction. It is not available to the user.
.BL
2 TYF
.BR
TYF - line type for function buttons
.BL
This is a privileged command in HELP mode which is only used
for patch file interaction. It is not available to the user.
.BL
2 PMI
.BR
PMI - Performance Monitor Initialise
.BL
This command is for Laser-Scan engineers only.
.BL
2 PME
.BR
PME - Performance Monitor End
.BL
This command is for Laser-Scan engineers only.
.BL
