.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 CLJ
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 WAD
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 ANA
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 EXI
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 MODe
.BR
MODe n
.BL
Select the scanning mode. MODe 0 scans in edge mode while MODe 1
scans in line mode.
.BL
2 DIRection
.BR
DIRection n
.BL
Select the scan direction. This is usually selected automatically
based on the direction of the required scan vector. A value of 0
results in hardware scans which are parallel to the X (horizontal)
direction, while a value of 1 results in scans which are parallel to Y.
.BL
2 FRQ
.BR
FRQ n
.BL
Set the scan frequency (range 0:6). If the scan frequency is altered
then the PHAse correction must be repeated (FB5 in CHECK mode).
.BL
2 WIDth
.BR
WIDth n
.BL
Set the effective scan width (sensible range 10:63). This value must be
multiplied by 64_*CRX/Y to obtain the width in HRD counts. It should be
noted that the LASERTRAK only has 4 hardware scan widths, corresponding
to WIDth 7,15,31 and 63. Intermediate values are obtained by ignoring
encounters outside the specified width. This means that the scan on
the LASERTRAK screen will double in size when WIDth is increased
from 15 to 16, for example.
.BL
2 PITch
.BR
PITch n
.BL
Set the scan pitch (sensible range 5:50 HRD counts).
.BL
2 WLO
.BR
WLO n
.BL
The value of this parameter should be 1. It should not be altered
by the user.
.BL
2 WHI
.BR
WHI n
.BL
The value of this parameter should be 255. It should not be altered
by the user.
.BL
2 TLO
.BR
TLO n - set digitiser threshold
.BL
The digitiser threshold is usually best set up by using the THReshold
command (FB9 in CHECK mode),
or by enabling automatic thresholding (TSW 0). If TLO is used,
the argument should be in the range 1:255.
.BL
2 TSW
.BR
TSW n - select automatic/manual thresholding
.BL
TSW 0 selects automatic thresholding, while TSW 1 selects
manual threshold (set using THReshold - FB9 in CHECK mode).
If automatic thresholding
is used, command THReshold will yield a horizontal line on the
close-up screen.
.BL
2 TMS
.BR
TMS n - set timeshare factor - not implemented
.BL
This command is reserved for possible future use.
.BL
2 CRX
.BR
CRX r - set counts ratio in X
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2) in CHECK mode.
.BL
2 CRY
.BR
CRY r - set counts ratio in Y
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2) in CHECK mode.
.BL
2 OFX
.BR
OFX r - set red/blue offset in X
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2) in CHECK mode.
.BL
2 OFY
.BR
OFY r - set red/blue offset in Y
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2) in CHECK mode.
.BL
2 PHX
.BR
PHX r - set phase correction in X
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the PHAse command (FB5) in CHECK mode.
.BL
2 PHY
.BR
PHY r - set phase correction in Y
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the PHAse command (FB5) in CHECK mode.
.BL
2 THK
.BR
THK r - thickness of line feature
.BL
This is the value entered in the IFF TH entry. It is
used for paintout unless over-ridden by PTH (q.v.).
.BL
Sensible range: 20 to 200 HRD counts. Typical value: 40 HRD counts
.BL
2 PTH
.BR
PTH r - paintout thickness
.BL
Thickness of line for paintout. If PTH is less than or equal to
zero, THK (q.v.) is used.
.BL
Typical value: 100 HRD counts
.BL
2 CLU
.BR
CLU r - chaining limit (normal to scan direction)
.BL
CLU is used to determine whether a point belongs on the
end of a growing chain element. It is the tolerance along
the line being followed.
.BL
CLU is currently only relevant to edge-mode small feature
scans; its use in general line following has been superseded.
.BL
See also CLV, CLW, CLX.
.BL
Typical value: 2 pitches
.BL
2 CLV
.BR
CLV r - chaining limit (parallel to scan direction)
.BL
CLV is used to determine whether a point belongs on the
end of a growing chain element. It is the tolerance across
the line being followed.
.BL
See also CLU, CLW, CLX.
.BL
Typical value: 2 pitches
.BL
2 CLW
.BR
CLW r - chaining limit (width change)
.BL
CLW originally determined whether a point belonged on the
end of a growing chain element by comparing the width
between adjacent scans (in line mode). It is currently unused.
.BL
See also CLU, CLV, CLX.
.BL
Typical value: 2 pitches (historical)
.BL
2 CLX
.BR
CLX r - chaining limit for new chains
.BL
CLX is the chaining tolerance used to grow the first
few points in a new chain (when the context is poor).
.BL
See also CLU, CLV, CLW.
.BL
Typical value: 3 pitches
.BL
2 ETA
.BR
ETA r - preliminary filtering tolerance
.BL
The LASERTRAK returns encounters separated along the line
by one PITch (assuming the line is continuous). This data
density is usually far too high, and a cheap filter is applied
based on ETA, which is essentially a lateral tolerance.
The more intelligent (and expensive) algorithms such as
the H, S and E filter (q.v.) only 'see' the data after
this initial filtering.
.BL
Hence for essentially straight-line data considerable
computational savings can be made by increasing ETA.
However, for complex, tortuous data it is important
that ETA is not too large or no amount of experimenting
with H, S and E will give a pleasing result.
.BL
Sensible range: 0.5 to 6 HRD counts
.BL
2 GAP
.BR
GAP r
.BL
GAP is the largest distance which can be 'ignored' by LASERAID
(e.g. when following pecked lines). It is also used in determining
the chain element quality (see 'chain__quality').
.BL
Sensible range: 80 to 400 HRD counts (assuming ID is large enough)
.BL
2 SHArpness
.BR
SHArpness r
.BL
SHArpness is the cosine of the sharpest corner which can
be negotiated.
Some examples are:
.BL
SHA#-1.0 - can go backwards (unlimited)
.BR
SHA#-0.7 - 135 degrees
.BR
SHA##0.0 - 90 degrees
.BR
SHA##0.7 - 45 degrees ('tunnel vision')
.BL
2 DIF
.BR
DIF r - 'wide' line criterion
.BL
A track is judged to have become 'wide' (for point positioning,
etc.) if its width is now greater than (1 + DIF) times the mean
track-width.
.BL
Typical value: 0.8
.BL
2 STIffness
.BR
STIffness r
.BL
Minimum length of line used to estimate track position and
direction. This may be 1 HRD count now.
.BL
Typical value: 1 HRD count
.BL
2 SMAllness
.BR
SMAllness r - smallest appendable chain element
.BL
SMAllness is the length of the smallest appendable
chain element (in units of the PITch). It only applies between scans.
.BL
SMAllness is also used in determining the chain element quality
(see 'chain__quality').
.BL
Typical value: 2 pitches (must NOT be zero)
.BL
2 BETa
.BR
BETa r - trackjump test criterion
.BL
Trackjumping is hopping between two adjacent lines.
This test assumes that we've already passed the NEArness and PRL
(q.v.) criteria.
.BL
If the line joining the current end of the track to the near end
of the next chain element makes too great an angle with either
the track or the chain element, we've trackjumped.
.BL
A larger value of BETa reduces the chances of trackjumping, but
makes LASERAID less able to cope with data imperfections.
.BL
Typical value: 0.1 (cosine)
.BL
2 NEArness
.BR
NEArness r - proximity criterion for trackjump test
.BL
If the next chain element is closer to the end of the current track
than NEArness, don't
perform the trackjump test (i.e. don't check for hopping between two
adjacent tracks). NEArness is expressed in units of the PITch.
.BL
If NEArness is small LASERAID is less likely to trackjump, but
may have difficulty negotiating corners in thick tortuous lines.
.BL
See also BETa and PRL.
.BL
Sensible range: 3 to 6 pitches (must NOT be zero)
.BL
2 PRL
.BR
PRL r - parallelism criterion for trackjump test
.BL
PRL is the cosine of the angle between the next chain element and
the current track direction.
If the chains are less parallel (cosine smaller) than PRL, don't
perform the trackjump test (i.e. don't check for hopping between two
adjacent tracks).
.BL
See also BETa and NEArness.
.BL
Typical value: 0.0 (i.e. almost never forbid trackjump test)
.BL
2 BIAs
.BR
BIAs r
.BL
BIAs is essentially an obsolete concept now. It is added to the
'quality' of each chain element with the aim of persuading
LASERAID to go right, straight-on or left depending on the
sign (negative, zero, positive). See also 'chain__quality'.
.BL
The latest chain-appending strategy takes care of this automatically.
.BL
Typical value: 0
.BL
2 MPN
.BR
MPN r - tolerance for backtrack checking ('nearness')
.BL
This is the distance tolerance to use when performing
the backtrack check (see BCH, MPB). If it is too small LASERAID
may become prone to backtracking, but if it is too large LASERAID
will be unable to follow around tight 'hairpin' bends.
.BL
Typical value: 50 HRD counts
.BL
2 TIK
.BR
TIK r - length of arms of control point ticks
.BL
LASERAID creates four three-point tick features in IFF layer 0
corresponding to the measured control points. The length of
the arms of these ticks is set by TIK.
.BL
Typical value: 500 HRD counts
.BL
2 SQT
.BR
SQT r - squaring tolerance
.BL
SQT is used with LASERAIDs in-built SQUare command (q.v.). This
is rather crude and really intended for demonstration purposes
only.
.BL
Typical value: 30 degrees
.BL
2 LEN
.BR
LEN r - 'quality' weight for chain length
.BL
See 'chain__quality' for a discussion of this parameter.
.BL
Typical value: 0.01
.BL
2 ANG
.BR
ANG r - 'quality' weight for chain angle
.BL
See 'chain__quality' for a discussion of this parameter.
.BL
Typical value: 3
.BL
2 DST
.BR
DST r - 'quality' weight for chain distance
.BL
See 'chain__quality' for a discussion of this parameter.
.BL
Typical value: 2
.BL
2 WTH
.BR
WTH r - 'quality' weight for chain-width change
.BL
See 'chain__quality' for a discussion of this parameter.
.BL
Typical value: 0.8
.BL
2 CRC
.BR
CRC r - 'crushing' cosine
.BL
Crushing is a form of filtering and smoothing combined. It
is used in junction recognition. CRC, being a cosine value, should
always be close to 1.0.
.BL
Typical value: 0.985
.BL
2 CRD
.BR
CRD r - 'crushing' distance
.BL
Crushing is a form of filtering and smoothing combined. It
is used in junction recognition. CRD should be of the order of
(within a factor of two of) the mean line-width.
.BL
Typical value: 40 HRD counts
.BL
2 SPD
.BR
SPD r - Suppress Paintout Distance
.BL
In order to 'spot' a previously measured junction when line following,
a small amount of each captured arm must be left unpainted. The
amount which must be left depends on whether junction 'snapping' is
enabled. If a full junction scan must be performed every time (JNC
greater than 4) a fairly large region must be left (SPD 300 might be
typical). If 'snapping' is enabled (JNC less than 4), LASERAID is
able to choose an appropriate paintout gap automatically. This mechanism
is invoked by setting SPD negative (usually the existing value is simply
negated, e.g. SPD -300).
.BL
The units are HRD counts.
.BL
2 STH
.BR
STH r - single point paintout thickness
.BL
Point features (i.e. those captured in POINT mode) are painted out
using a filled square of size STH.
.BL
Typical value: 200 HRD counts
.BL
2 ID
.BR
ID n - scan vector length
.BL
Sensible range: 100 to 2000 HRD counts
.BL
2 HOLe
.BR
HOLe n - maximum gap to chain across in SMF
.BL
This is used in line-mode small feature capture (SMF in MAIN mode).
It performs a somewhat similar function to CLU (q.v.) in edge-mode
small feature capture.
.BL
Typical value: 45 HRD counts
.BL
2 RIPple
.BR
RIPple n - maximum lateral ripple for chaining in SMF
.BL
This is used in line-mode small feature capture (SMF in MAIN mode).
It performs a somewhat similar function to CLV (q.v.) in normal
line following.
.BL
Typical value: 80 HRD counts
.BL
2 CRS
.BR
CRS n - behaviour at 'crossings' (junctions)
.BL
Specify the arm to be selected by LASERAID when a junction is
captured. Possible values are:
.BL
CRS#-1 - turn left
.BR
CRS##0 - go straight on
.BR
CRS##1 - turn right
.BL
LASERAID will make its judgement based on the current direction
and, of course, which arms are available. Depending on the
value of JNC (q.v.) LASERAID can be instructed to select that
arm and proceed automatically.
.BL
2 MPB
.BR
MPB n - number of master points for backtrack checking
.BL
This is the number of master points to use when performing
the backtrack check (see BCH, MPN).
.BL
Typical value: 12
.BL
2 CHF
.BR
This command is reserved for possible future use.
.BL
2 INI
.BR
INI n - initialisation command macro number
.BL
This is the macro number to use when starting a feature. Allowed
values are 15 for a normal line type (enables FINd/FUMble if selected
in MAIN mode), or 25 for a line type with junction spotting.
.BL
Odd effects are observed if you specify the wrong INI (in particular,
FINd stops working).
.BL
2 HCH
.BR
HCH n - hatching style for area paintout
.BL
Set the hatching style for area paintout (in edge-mode line
following). This affects the speed of paintout. Allowed values are:
.BL
HCH 0 - total infill with lines of thickness PTH (q.v.)
.BR
HCH 1 - horizontal lines with separation PTH
.BR
HCH 2 - vertical lines with separation PTH
.BR
HCH 3 - both directions with separation PTH
.BL
Typical value: 3
.BL
2 ECHo
.BR
ECHo n - command echoing
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
echoing of the command macros as they are obeyed. If
enabled when the program is exited, this value is preserved
and the patch file parameters are also echoed the next time
the patch file is used.
.BL
This facility is usually disabled.
.BL
2 Vectors
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 BCH
.BR
BCH n - backtrack check
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
backtrack checking (to ensure LASERAID is not following back
down the line it just captured).
.BL
It is usual to enable this check (see also MPB, MPN).
.BL
2 TCH
.BR
TCH n - temporary checks
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
temporary checks and diagnostic graphics.
.BL
It is intended for use by Laser-Scan engineers, but can
sometimes be useful for demonstrations.
.BL
2 EDG
.BR
EDG n - use of edge information
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
the use of any edge information found when following
in line mode (MODe 1).
.BL
Laser-Scan recommends that this is always enabled.
.BL
2 SMOothing
.BR
SMOothing n - chain smoothing
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
chain smoothing prior to master point extraction.
.BL
Laser-Scan recommends that this is always enabled.
.BL
2 VEX
.BR
VEX n - vertex extraction
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
vertex extraction. After the master points have been generated
they are re-examined to ensure that any superfluous ones are
removed. This helps to clean up building features, etc. where
only vertex points are required.
.BL
In fact, Laser-Scan recommends that vertex extraction is turned
on for ALL line types, as the improvement in data quality (even
on smooth contours) more than offsets the slight additional cpu
overhead.
.BL
2 JNC
.BR
JNC n - junction recognition
.BL
This is a switch to enable or disable junction recognition.
It is bitwise decoded as follows:
.BL
Assuming a starting value of zero,
.BR
Add 1 if junction recognition is required at all, then
.BR
Add 2 if the program should accept the junction automatically, then
.BR
Add 4 if the program should NOT automatically snap to existing
junctions, but should perform a complete junction scan each time.
.BL
The most usual settings are:
.BR
JNC 0 - junctions disabled
.BR
JNC 3 - junctions enabled, 'auto-accept-and-go' enabled
.BL
Another useful setting is JNC 2. In this state, FPJ (FB13) will
turn junction recognition on or off, enabling 'auto-accept-and-go'
at the same time. See CRS for information on automatic arm selection.
.BL
Remember that line types set up to spot junctions should specify
'INI#25' in the type table (see INI, PTY, VAR).
.BL
2 INVerse
.BR
INVerse n - inverse polarity
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
'inverse polarity' mode. This enables the centre lines of
double-banked rivers etc. to be captured.
.BL
2 BRF
.BR
BRF n - brief messages
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
'brief' messages. This is intended for experienced users
or demonstration sessions where messages such as 'feature closed'
and 'abandoned' clutter up the close-up screen and are
unnecessary. In brief mode the terminal bell is
rung to indicate closure, end of feature, etc.
.BL
2 ELF
.BR
ELF n - Edge-mode Line Following
.BL
This is a switch to enable (n = 1) or disable (n = 0)
edge-mode line following. It is set automatically
based on the MODe (q.v.) value for the current line TYPe,
although that value may be explicitly over-ridden by use
of this command (for the benefit of Laser-Scan engineers).
.BL
2 Display
.BR
This is a macro component.
.BL
2 EPS
.BR
EPS r - edge-mode chain merging tolerance
.BL
Used in edge-mode small feature (ESF) to overlay the
results of two scans.
.BL
Typical value: 15 HRD counts
.BL
2 LIMit
.BR
LIMit n r
.BL
The LIMits are a set of miscellaneous values required by the
line-following
algorithms. Optimum values have been ascertained by Laser-Scan
and users should not attempt to modify them unless so
instructed by a Laser-Scan engineer.
.BL
2 Weight
.BR
Weight n r
.BL
The Weights are a set of miscellaneous values required by the
line-following
algorithms. Optimum values have been ascertained by Laser-Scan
and users should not attempt to modify them unless so
instructed by a Laser-Scan engineer.
.BL
2 Hfilter
.BR
H r - filtering parameter (maximum lateral deviation)
.BL
When any 'backlogged' (potential) data point becomes further
than H from the least-squares line through those points,
a 'master point' is generated.
.BL
See also ETA, E and S.
.BL
Sensible range: 4 to 20 HRD counts. Typical value: 8
.BL
2 Sfilter
.BR
S r - filtering parameter (maximum separation)
.BL
When line following, no two successive master points may be
further apart than S. Setting S to zero disables this mechanism
(no points are forced out purely on distance criteria).
.BL
See also ETA, H and E.
.BL
Sensible range: 500 to 32000 HRD counts (0 to disable)
.BL
2 Efilter
.BR
E r - filtering parameter (minimum separation)
.BL
When line following, no two successive master points may be
closer than E. Special rules apply for junctions, however.
.BL
See also ETA, H and S.
.BL
Sensible range: 20 to 100 HRD counts
.BL
2 MPL
.BR
MPL n - output master points at this total
.BL
When MPL master points have been accumulated, some are
flushed to the IFF file, leaving MPF (q.v.) still in the buffer.
.BL
Typical value: 80
.BL
2 MPF
.BR
MPF n - keep this many master points 'in hand'
.BL
When MPL (q.v.) master points have been accumulated, some
are flushed to the IFF file leaving MPF still in the buffer.
.BL
Typical value: 20
.BL
2 MPX
.BR
MPX n - maximum number of master points in a feature
.BL
Typical value: 2900, limit: 32767
.BL
2 SEParation
.BR
SEParation r - separation of lines for paintout
.BL
Typical value: 0.010 mm (on photochromic film)
.BL
2 SPOt
.BR
SPOt r - size of beam for paintout
.BL
Typical value: 0.016 mm (on photochromic film)
.BL
2 SCT
.BR
SCT n - maximum fiducial scatter
.BL
Abandon fiducial (and control point etc.) measurement if more
than half the measured positions exceed this scatter.
.BL
Typical value: 30 HRD counts
.BL
2 REPeat
.BR
REPeat n - number of 'dummy' fiducial scans
.BL
The number of scans performed to allow the LASERTRAK to 'settle'
before fiducial measurements are taken.
.BL
Range: 0 to 4. Typical value: 1
.BL
2 AVErage
.BR
AVErage n - number of scan used to determine fiducial position
.BL
Typical value: 5
.BL
2 OFF
.BR
OFF r - expected scatter of fiducial measurements
.BL
Typical value: 8 HRD counts
.BL
2 QUAlity
.BR
QUAlity r - minimum acceptable fiducial quality
.BL
When measuring a control point or check fiducial, LASERAIDs internal
'quality' assessment must be greater than this for the object to
be found.
.BL
Typical value: 0.3
.BL
2 GRId
.BR
GRId r - calibration grid-square size
.BL
The size of the calibration grid squares. This is
only used for normalisation purposes and is not crucial.
.BL
Typical value: 40 mm
.BL
2 FLE
.BR
FLE n - set red laser focus level
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the FOCus command (FB13) in CHECK mode.
.BL
2 FPR
.BR
FPR n - following priority
.BL
Process priority when line-following.
This will have a detrimental effect on other users if set too high.
See also PPR, WPR.
.BL
Requires ALTPRI privilege, or sufficient base priority.
.BL
Typical value: 4
.BL
2 PPR
.BR
PPR n - paintout priority
.BL
Process priority when painting out.
This will have a detrimental effect on other users if set too high.
See also FPR, WPR.
.BL
Requires ALTPRI privilege, or sufficient base priority.
.BL
Typical value: 4
.BL
2 WPR
.BR
WPR n - waiting priority
.BL
Process priority when waiting for input
(i.e. when interacting with the tracker ball etc.).
See also FPR, PPR.
.BL
Requires ALTPRI privilege, or sufficient base priority.
.BL
Typical value: 4
.BL
2 FCT
.BR
FCT n - Force CP Type
.BL
When the CP command is given in MAIN mode, then if CFT is 1
the CCP command (q.v.) is obeyed instead to do a combined
CALibration and Control Point measurement (assumes that the map has
a superimposed grid).
.BL
The normal value is 0.
.BL
2 PNT
.BR
PNT n - default point feature mode
.BL
PNT determines the default action to be taken when POInt (FB6 in
MAIN mode)
is pressed to enter POINT mode (q.v.). If PNT is 0 the
default action will be to look for a cross ('+' or 'x') or a
small ring, whereas if PNT is 1 a scan will be made to search
for 'square building' features (represented by filled squares).
Note that once in POINT mode both types of scan are available;
PNT only determines the action when FB6 in MAIN mode is first pressed.
.BL
More help is available in POINT mode.
.BL
2 JAT
.BR
JAT r - Junction arm Angle Tolerance.
.BL
Tolerance for deciding which arm matches the current
track.
.BL
Typical value: 40 degrees
.BL
2 JPT
.BR
JPT r - Junction Position Tolerance
.BL
If two junctions are closer together than JPT they
are merged into one. Also, when locating an existing junction, if
the LASERTRAK cursor is within JPT of the junction then it is found.
.BL
The value of JPT should be approximately
(i.e. within a factor of two of) the mean line-width.
.BL
Typical value: 40 HRD counts.
.BL
2 JWT
.BR
JWT r - Junction arm-Width Tolerance
.BL
Do not spot a junction if the line width falls below
JWT_*(current track-width). Prevents 'flapping' in poor
quality data where the linework may contain holes.
.BL
Range: 0.0 (disabled) to 0.8. Typical value: 0.3.
.BL
2 PPP
.BR
PPP - Print Primary (user) Parameters
.BR
PUP
.BL
Display the parameters which the operator may have
to vary in the course of setting up LASERAID to follow
a particular type of linework. See also the PAP command
which lists additional parameters available to the system
manager.
.BL
2 PAP
.BR
PAP - Print All Parameters
.BL
Display all the parameters to which the system manager
has access. Note that most of the parameters which
do not appear in the basic operator set (see the PPP command)
are effectively constants and only require modification
in order to follow unusual or poor quality linework.
.BL
If you are unable to persuade LASERAID to follow satisfactorily,
a sample negative should be sent to Laser-Scan, who will be
able to advise you on optimum parameter settings.
.BL
2 PSP
.BR
PSP - Print Scanner Parameters
.BL
Display the parameters which are relevant to the scanning process.
.BL
2 PLP
.BR
PLP - Print Line-following Parameters
.BL
Display the parameters which are relevant to the line-following
process.
.BL
2 PLW
.BR
PLW - print LIMits and Weights
.BL
Display the LIMit and Weight parameters. These should be
only be altered after consultation with Laser-Scan.
.BL
2 POD
.BR
POD - print oddments
.BL
Display parameters which do not fall into  any well-defined category
(see also PAP).
.BL
1 CONFIRM__MODE
.BR
In this mode the system is basically waiting  for  a  YES/NO
answer, or permission to commence an action.
.BR
2 FBs
.BR
For details of the current function buttons type '?'.
.BR
Use ?FB1 for information on FB1 (which is context-dependent).
.BL
2 FB1
.BR
When defining a window for windowed paintout, FB1 resets the origin of
the refresh box to the current cursor position.
.BL
2 OK
.BR
OK (FB4)
.BR
YES (FB4)
.BR
GO (FB4)
.BL
Indicate acceptance.
.BL
2 NO
.BR
NO (FB16)
.BR
ABAndon (FB16)
.BR
ABOrt (FB16)
.BR
QUIt (FB16)
.BL
Indicate rejection.
.BL
1 CHECK__MODE
.BR
This mode enables the LASERTRAK parameters to be set up ready for
digitising.
.BR
2 FBs
.BR
For details of the current function buttons type '?'.
.BL
2 STArt
.BR
STArt (FB1)
.BL
Set the start point of the required scan vector. If this is selected
in error then FB1 can be pressed again to choose the current cursor
position. When the start point has been defined, the length and
direction of the scan vector is
specified by the 'rubber-band' line attached to the cursor.
.BL
2 OCR
.BR
OCR (FB2) - set red/blue Offset and Counts Ratio
.BL
Used in conjunction with WHL (FB3), this command causes a 'goal-post'
graph to be drawn on the close-up screen. A good measurement is
indicated by a nearly straight diagonal line which overlays the
45 degree line. This set-up should be performed on horizontal and
vertical 'white lines'; each measurement should be performed at least
twice and a wide line type should be used (e.g. TYPe 1).
.BL
2 WHL
.BR
WHL (FB3) - construct a WHite Line for set-up
.BL
Although primarily intended for use with OCR (FB2), other checks
such as THReshold and PHAse may also be carried out on the 'white
line' constructed by this command. A wide line type (e.g. TYPe 1)
should be specified before giving this command if an OCR set-up
is to be performed.
.BL
2 TXZ
.BR
TXZ (FB4) - clear the close-up screen
.BL
The Tektronix screen is cleared (zeroed).
.BL
2 PHAse
.BR
PHAse (FB5)
.BL
Set the phase correction. A horizontal line is drawn on the close-up
screen and a series of scans are performed, one for each time the
scan width CHANGES in the type table (e.g.#if#types#1#to#7 had
widths of 63 15 15 20 15 15 20, then 5 scans would be performed).
Each scan results in a line which crosses the horizontal line on the
close-up screen; that is the correct phase for that scan width.
The phase should be measured on both horizontal and vertical lines, and
the set-up must be repeated if the scan frequency is altered.
.BL
2 CURsor
.BR
CURsor (FB8)
.BL
Draw a close-up view of the area around the LASERTRAK cursor on
the Tektronix screen, then put up the Tektronix cursor. When a
character is typed the LASERTRAK cursor is moved to the equivalent
position. This command can be used for fine positioning of the
LASERTRAK cursor (cf. the CLOse-up command).
.BL
2 THReshold
.BR
THReshold (FB9)
.BL
Set the digitiser threshold. A threshold graph is drawn on the
close-up screen and the Tektronix cursor is activated. Usually
the threshold which is required is somewhere in the middle of
the plateau region of the graph (see the users' guide for more
information).
.BL
2 CLOse-up
.BR
CLOse-up (FB12)
.BL
Draw a close-up view of the area around the LASERTRAK cursor on
the Tektronix screen (cf. the CURsor command).
.BL
2 FOCus
.BR
FOCus (FB13)
.BL
Set the red laser focus. A 'high' threshold should first be set
using the THReshold command (select a value about half-way up the
trailing edge of the threshold graph). The FOCus command then causes
a focus graph to be drawn and the Tektronix cursor is activated.
Perform this check in both axes and choose the highest point of overlap
of the two graphs (if the graphs do not overlap at all then the
digitising laser spot is astigmatic and may require adjustment).
Remember to reset the threshold afterwards.
.BL
2 QUL
.BR
QUL (FB14) - check quality of line position measurement
.BL
This check should produce an approximately horizontal line on the
close-up screen. It is usually performed after OCR (FB2).
.BL
2 QUW
.BR
QUW (FB15) - check quality of line width measurement
.BL
This check should produce an approximately horizontal line on the
close-up screen. It is usually performed after OCR (FB2).
.BL
2 ABAndon
.BR
ABAndon (FB16)
.BL
Abandon CHECK mode, returning to MAIN mode.
.BL
2 ZERo
.BR
This command is for Laser-Scan engineers only.
.BL
2 RFK
.BR
RFK n - set ReFresh 'Kick' rate
.BL
This command is for Laser-Scan engineers only.
.BL
2 TBK
.BR
TBK n - set Tracker-Ball 'Kick' rate
.BL
This command is for Laser-Scan engineers only.
.BL
2 ERRor
.BR
Repeatedly scan a line (specified using STArt) and check the
resulting hardware encounters for consistency. If an error is
found the scan will stop and a message will be displayed,
otherwise FB16 can be used to abandon scanning.
.BL
2 SPH
.BR
SPH - Software PHase (not implemented)
.BL
This command is reserved for possible future use.
.BL
2 PSP
.BR
PSP - Print Scanner Parameters
.BL
Display the parameters which are relevant to the scanning process.
.BL
2 TYPe
.BR
TYPe n
.BL
Select line type n.
.BL
2 PTY
.BR
PTY - Print TYpe table
.BL
Display the available line types.
.BL
2 MODe
.BR
MODe n
.BL
Select the scanning mode. MODe 0 scans in edge mode while MODe 1
scans in line mode.
.BL
2 DIRection
.BR
DIRection n
.BL
Select the scan direction. This is usually selected automatically
based on the direction of the required scan vector. A value of 0
results in hardware scans which are parallel to the X (horizontal)
direction, while a value of 1 results in scans which are parallel to Y.
.BL
2 FRQ
.BR
FRQ n
.BL
Set the scan frequency (range 0:6). If the scan frequency is altered
then the PHAse (FB5) correction must be repeated.
.BL
2 WIDth
.BR
WIDth n
.BL
Set the effective scan width (sensible range 10:63). This value must be
multiplied by 64_*CRX/Y to obtain the width in HRD counts. It should be
noted that the LASERTRAK only has 4 hardware scan widths, corresponding
to WIDth 7,15,31 and 63. Intermediate values are obtained by ignoring
encounters outside the specified width. This means that the scan on
the LASERTRAK screen will double in size when WIDth is increased
from 15 to 16, for example.
.BL
2 PITch
.BR
PITch n
.BL
Set the scan pitch (sensible range 5:50 HRD counts).
.BL
2 WLO
.BR
WLO n
.BL
The value of this parameter should be 1. It should not be altered
by the user.
.BL
2 WHI
.BR
WHI n
.BL
The value of this parameter should be 255. It should not be altered
by the user.
.BL
2 TLO
.BR
TLO n - set digitiser threshold
.BL
The digitiser threshold is usually best set up by using the THReshold
command (FB9),
or by enabling automatic thresholding (TSW 0). If TLO is used,
the argument should be in the range 1:255.
.BL
2 TSW
.BR
TSW n - select automatic/manual thresholding
.BL
TSW 0 selects automatic thresholding, while TSW 1 selects
manual threshold (set using THReshold - FB9). If automatic thresholding
is used, command THReshold will yield a horizontal line on the
close-up screen.
.BL
2 TMS
.BR
TMS n - set timeshare factor - not implemented
.BL
This command is reserved for possible future use.
.BL
2 CRX
.BR
CRX r - set counts ratio in X
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2).
.BL
2 CRY
.BR
CRY r - set counts ratio in Y
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2).
.BL
2 OFX
.BR
OFX r - set red/blue offset in X
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2).
.BL
2 OFY
.BR
OFY r - set red/blue offset in Y
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the OCR command (FB2).
.BL
2 PHX
.BR
PHX r - set phase correction in X
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the PHAse command (FB5).
.BL
2 PHY
.BR
PHY r - set phase correction in Y
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the PHAse command (FB5).
.BL
2 FLE
.BR
FLE n - set red laser focus level
.BL
Except in extraordinary circumstances, this parameter should
only be set by means of the FOCus command (FB13).
.BL
1 CALIBRATE__MODE
.BR
This mode enables grid intersections to be measured for calibration
purposes.
.BR
2 FBs
.BR
For details of the current function buttons type '?'.
.BL
2 AUTo
.BR
AUTo (FB 2)
.BL
Perform an automatic measurement. The LASERTRAK cursor is
left over the intersection position if one is found, otherwise
a warning is issued.
.BL
2 OK
.BR
OK (FB4)
.BR
YES (FB4)
.BR
GO (FB4)
.BL
Accept the measurement.
.BL
2 MANual
.BR
MANual (FB8)
.BL
Perform a manual measurement using the close-up screen and cursor.
Position the cross-hairs over the required position on the close-up
screen and type any character on the keyboard.
.BL
2 SKIp
.BR
SKIp (FB12)
.BL
Skip this intersection. Pressing SKIp rather than OK (FB4) causes
the intersection to be ignored, and LASERAID moves on to the next.
.BL
2 CONtinuous
.BR
CONtinuous (FB13)
.BL
Select continuous, automatic measurement. The default operation
is for the program to pause after each intersection measurement
for the operator to accept it. Continuous measurement enables
LASERAID to proceed automatically, accepting each measurement in
turn and proceeding to the next intersection. If a bad intersection
is found, automatic measurement will cease and the operator will
be invited to enter manual mode. The CONtinuous option may
subsequently be re-activated by pressing FB13 again.
.BL
2 NO
.BR
NO (FB16)
.BR
ABAndon (FB16)
.BR
ABOrt (FB16)
.BR
QUIt (FB16)
.BL
Abandon CALIBRATE mode, returning to MAIN mode.
.BL
1 LOCATE__MODE
.BR
In this mode the feature(s) nearest the LASERTRAK cursor have
been LOCated.
.BR
2 FBs
.BR
For details of the current function buttons type '?'.
.BL
2 NXT
.BR
NXT (FB1) - get next feature
.BL
Get the next feature from the 'found' list (cyclically).
The feature is refreshed on the LASERTRAK and is 'in hand'.
.BL
A maximum of four features can be held in the list.
.BL
2 REPaint
.BR
REPaint (FB4)
.BL
Repaint the refreshed feature.
.BL
2 DELete
.BR
DELete (FB13)
.BL
Delete the refreshed feature. Note that it cannot subsequently
be recovered.
.BL
2 ABAndon 
.BR
ABAndon (FB16)
.BL
Abandon LOCATE mode, returning to MAIN mode.
.BL
