1 POINT__MODE
.BR
This mode enables single-point features to be digitised.
.BR
2 FBs
.BR
For details of the current function buttons type '?'.
.BL
2 DPO
.BR
DPO (FB1) - perform and draw a traditional POINT mode scan
.BL
Scan for a 'traditional' point feature ('+', 'x', or 'o'),
drawing the results on the close-up screen. If a feature is
found the LASERTRAK cursor is positioned over the feature and
a dot is displayed in refresh. FB4 (OK) can be then be used to
accept the feature.
.BL
The normal command to use for this type of scan is POI (FB2)
which does not draw on the close-up screen.
.BL
2 POI
.BR
POI (FB2) - perform a traditional POINT mode scan
.BL
Scan for a 'traditional' point feature ('+', 'x', or 'o').
If a feature is
found the LASERTRAK cursor is positioned over the feature and
a dot is displayed in refresh. FB4 (OK) can be then be used to
accept the feature.
.BL
DPO (FB1) is identical to POI, except that the results of the
scan are drawn on the close-up screen.
.BL
2 OK
.BR
OK (FB4) - accept the point feature(s)
.BR
YES (FB4)
.BR
GO (FB4)
.BL
Accept any refreshed point feature(s). If more than one feature
is accepted, the feature number is incremented as usual.
.BL
If no features were found by the scan, the cursor position is
read and a feature is created there. In 'square building' mode,
a warning message will be output to indicate that the orientation
of the feature has not been set.
.BL
2 DSQ
.BR
DSQ (FB5) - perform and draw a 'square building' scan
.BL
Scan for one or more 'square building' features (represented by
filled squares), drawing the results on the close-up screen.
Any recognised objects are highlighted in refresh, with the number
found indicated alongside (the scan box is
also shown; this may be moved if required and another scan performed).
.BL
OK (FB4) will accept all refreshed objects in one go (creating separate
oriented point features), or each object
may be selected individually using NXT (FB8). DRF (FB7) will draw
any refreshed object(s) on the close-up screen.
.BL
The normal command to use for this type of scan is SQP (FB6)
which does not draw on the close-up screen.
.BL
2 SQP
.BR
SQP (FB6) - perform a 'square building' scan
.BL
Scan for one or more 'square building' features (represented by
filled squares).
Any recognised objects are highlighted in refresh, with the number
found indicated alongside (the scan box is
also shown; this may be moved if required and another scan performed).
.BL
OK (FB4) will accept all refreshed objects in one go (creating separate
oriented point features), or each object
may be selected individually using NXT (FB8). DRF (FB7) will draw
any refreshed object(s) on the close-up screen.
.BL
DSQ (FB5) is identical to SQP, except that the results of the
scan are drawn on the close-up screen.
.BL
2 DRF
.BR
DRF (FB7) - draw selected 'square building' feature(s)
.BL
Draw any refreshed 'square building' features on the close-up screen.
A cross is drawn inside the 'least-squares' quadrilateral to indicate
the position and orientation of the point feature.
.BL
2 NXT
.BR
NXT (FB8) - select next 'square building' feature
.BL
Cycle through the found objects in turn, allowing selected ones
to be accepted.
.BL
2 CLOse-up
.BR
CLOse-up (FB 12)
.BL
Draw a close-up view of the area around the LASERTRAK cursor on
the Tektronix screen.
.BL
2 ABAndon
.BR
ABAndon (FB16)
.BR
NO (FB16)
.BR
ABOrt (FB16)
.BR
QUIt (FB16)
.BL
Abandon POINT mode, returning to MAIN mode. Any unaccepted
point feature(s) will be discarded.
.BL
2 AC
.BR
AC type value [text] - Ancillary Code
.BL
Create an Ancillary Code (AC) in the current point feature.
The current Ancillary Code Base (ACB) value (if any) is added
to the AC type.
.BL
Note that if several point features are being accepted in one
go (i.e. in 'square building' mode) then only the FIRST feature will
contain ACs created using this command. All of the features
will, however, contain the Standing Ancillary Code (SAC) if
one has been defined (see MAIN mode).
.BL
The AC 'value' is examined for a decimal point, and
is stored as a real number if one is found. If the AC 'type' is 3
(INCLUDING the ACB), this is treated as a special case and its
value is ALWAYS stored as a real number.
.BL
